/*
Problem: Longest Consecutive Sequence

Description:
Given an unsorted array of integers, return the length of the longest
consecutive elements sequence.

Approach:
1. Store all elements in an unordered_set.
2. Traverse only the unique elements in the set.
3. A number is the starting element of a sequence only if (num - 1)
   does not exist in the set.
4. Count consecutive elements using the set.
5. Update the maximum sequence length.
*/

class Solution {
public:
    int longestConsecutive(vector<int>& nums) {
        if (nums.empty()) {
            return 0;
        }

        unordered_set<int> s;

        for (int num : nums) {
            s.insert(num);
        }

        int ans = 0;

        // Iterate over the set instead of the vector.
        // This avoids processing duplicate values multiple times.
        for (int num : s) {

            // If the previous consecutive element exists,
            // this is not the start of a sequence.
            if (s.find(num - 1) != s.end()) {
                continue;
            }

            int current = num;
            int length = 1;

            while (s.find(current + 1) != s.end()) {
                current++;
                length++;
            }

            ans = max(ans, length);
        }

        return ans;
    }
};

/*
Time Complexity: O(n)
Space Complexity: O(n)

Important Points:
1. Check (num - 1), NOT the previous index.
   Wrong:
       s.find(nums[i - 1])
   Correct:
       s.find(num - 1)

2. Use a separate variable (current/st) inside the while loop.
   Don't keep checking nums[i] because nums[i] never changes.

3. Reset length = 1 for every new sequence.

4. Store the maximum answer using:
       ans = max(ans, length);

5. Handle the empty array case before processing.

Common Mistakes I Made While Solving:
❌ Forgot nums.size().
❌ Used nums[i - 1] instead of num - 1.
❌ Declared length outside the loop.
❌ Returned length instead of ans.
❌ Forgot to update the moving variable (st/current).
❌ Missed the empty array check.

Why iterating over the vector may lead to TLE:
If nums contains many duplicate values, the same sequence can be
processed multiple times.

Example:
nums = [1,1,1,1,2,3,4]

Looping over nums:
1 -> counts sequence
1 -> counts sequence again
1 -> counts sequence again
...

Looping over unordered_set:
1 -> counts once
2 -> skipped
3 -> skipped
4 -> skipped

Thus, iterating over the set avoids repeated work on duplicates and is
the cleaner implementation.
*/
